Here's the proper approach using **Window lifecycle events** and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Save in **both** `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying` | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying` |
| Use `Preferences` for small values | It's fast and synchronous — critical since Android enforces a ~5s ANR timeout |
| Don't save in `OnDeactivated` | That fires for dialogs/split-screen — the app may never actually background |
| `OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch | The initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated`, so load initial state separately |

For larger drafts (images, rich content), serialize to a file instead of `Preferences`, but keep it fast.
